# TypeScript conventions

Aligned with Payload core team guidance; match the existing codebase first.

- Use **`import type`** for types; value imports separate, even from the same module.
- Prefer **`type` over `interface`**, except when extending external/library types.
- Prefer **functions over classes** (classes mainly for errors/adapters).
- Prefer **single object parameters** for new public/config-style APIs when it improves extensibility.
- Name booleans with **`is` / `has` / `can` / `should`** (e.g. `isProduction`, `hasUser`).
- Prefer **pure functions**; if you must mutate, return the mutated object rather than relying on void side effects.
- **Comments**: skip when obvious; use for non-obvious “why”, multi-step flows, or complex invariants. JSDoc on complex functions is fine when types alone are not enough.

## Payload logger

When using `payload.logger` (or project logger) with an object payload, use **`msg`** and **`err`** keys—not `message` / `error` as property names. Do not pass the Error as a second positional argument to `error()` if the API expects a single object/message shape.
